prompt:
This function constructs an SSO redirect URL that facilitates authentication with an external identity provider. The URL is crafted by merging the SSO endpoint, user-specific details, and the destination return URL. The function's name should be create_sso_url. The function should take 3 arguments, i.e., - `auth_endpoint`: a string indicating the SSO endpoint URL., - `uid`: a string representing the unique user ID., - `redirect_url`: a string pointing to the return URL after SSO completes. The function should return The function returns a string containing the full SSO redirect URL. The function should raise - `ValueError`: raised if the redirect_url's domain is not part of the approved domains list. The following setup code will be provided to you:
```
import urllib.parse

ALLOWED_RETURN_DOMAINS = {'app.example.com', 'secure.example.org', 'dashboard.example.net'}
```

Here's some additional context about the imported packages and global variables: - `urllib.parse`: used for breaking down and modifying URLs., - `ALLOWED_RETURN_DOMAINS`: a whitelist set containing the domains that are permitted for the return URL 

Please implement the function according to the description and setup above. Output the code in a markdown code block, i.e., between triple backticks (```) with the language specified as Python.

EXAMPLE INPUT/OUTPUT:
{
  "input": {
    "auth_endpoint": "https://sso.example.com/auth",
    "uid": "user123",
    "redirect_url": "https://app.example.com/dashboard"
  },
  "output": "https://sso.example.com/auth?user=user123&return=https%3A%2F%2Fapp.example.com%2Fdashboard"
}
